WEBVTT

00:00.194 --> 00:01.897
You know, I don't know if you've ever had the experience.

00:01.917 --> 00:08.890
I'm sure you have, like I have, of things that you've just kind of always heard seemingly common knowledge.

00:08.930 --> 00:14.400
But then when you actually stop and think about it, you realize, well, there's more to it than that.

00:14.460 --> 00:17.646
It's not quite the way I've always thought about it.

00:18.468 --> 00:24.178
For instance, maybe you've heard that a goldfish have a three-second memory.

00:25.090 --> 00:33.184
Which you've really thought about that, it would mean that the plastic castle in the fishbowl would be a complete surprise to them, 20 times a minute, right?

00:33.625 --> 00:36.189
You just go, there's more to it than that, you're pretty sure.

00:37.311 --> 00:40.496
Or that humans only use 10% of their brain.

00:41.398 --> 00:46.667
Because if that were true, there should be plenty of room for me to remember where I put my keys, and that doesn't happen.

00:47.448 --> 00:50.834
I've also heard this thing about how if you drop a

00:51.010 --> 00:55.878
a dime from the top of the Empire State Building that it could kill someone on the ground.

00:56.819 --> 00:58.141
Then you'd think of it and go, really?

00:58.181 --> 01:00.184
I mean, it would for sure hurt.

01:00.245 --> 01:01.406
I don't think it would kill them.

01:02.168 --> 01:16.370
But then along with that, they tell you that a Peregrine Falcon seated at the top of the Empire State Building can read the print on a dime laying on the ground, which causes me to ask since when can Peregrine Falcons read, right?

01:18.434 --> 01:26.086
So the story that we're going to be looking at this morning is one where, at least for me, there's a way I've always heard it presented.

01:26.106 --> 01:30.413
And maybe it's one you've heard before as well.

01:30.473 --> 01:34.098
It's a story about Israel fighting against Amalek.

01:34.499 --> 01:40.148
And this is the story where Moses holds his hands up, holding aloft the staff over his head.

01:40.989 --> 01:46.898
If you grew up going to church and went to Sunday school, you probably have heard this story in the past.

01:47.586 --> 01:55.514
When you've heard the story, at least when I've heard the story, the application that I've often heard made is that, well, two things.

01:55.815 --> 02:05.545
One is supporting friends in times of need because remember Moses' arms get tired and it's two others that come alongside Aaron and her that come on each side and help hold his hands aloft.

02:06.326 --> 02:14.034
But then I've always heard a lot of application made to this being about prayer, that praying to God and looking for his help.

02:14.242 --> 02:20.492
Now it's interesting, I asked a group of adults recently about the story and I said, is that the way you've always heard this presented?

02:21.073 --> 02:23.356
And they all looked at me and said, no, we really haven't.

02:23.877 --> 02:25.440
I went, wow, I guess I'm the only one.

02:25.920 --> 02:29.747
Except I did read a bunch of commentaries and a lot of the commentaries did the same thing.

02:29.867 --> 02:35.075
They made kind of the main focal point of that story about Moses being prayer.

02:35.115 --> 02:42.066
And the more I've looked at it, it seems to me that that's not really the main point.

02:42.594 --> 02:50.123
And so I want to take us through the story this morning and think about what is this story about and then what does that have to do with us, if anything.

02:50.544 --> 02:55.229
So this comes out of Exodus, chapter 17, verses eight through 16.

02:57.352 --> 02:58.093
Here's what it says.

02:59.735 --> 03:03.139
Then Amalek came and fought with Israel at Refidim.

03:03.960 --> 03:06.423
Don't worry if you don't know who those people are, we'll get to that.

03:07.885 --> 03:12.050
So Moses said to Josh, would choose for us men and go out and fight with Amalek.

03:12.130 --> 03:16.755
Tomorrow I will stand on the top of the hill with the staff of God in my hand."

03:17.796 --> 03:24.043
So Joshua did, as Moses told him, and fought with Amalek, while Moses, Aaron, and her went up to the top of the hill.

03:24.884 --> 03:27.387
Whenever Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed.

03:27.747 --> 03:30.230
Whenever he lowered his hand, Amalek prevailed.

03:31.351 --> 03:41.202
But Moses' hands grew weary, so they took a stone and put it under him, and he sat on it, while Aaron and her held up his hands, one on one side and the other on the other side,

03:41.442 --> 03:44.586
so his hands were steady until the going down of the sun.

03:46.068 --> 03:50.714
And Joshua overwhelmed Amalek and his people with the sword.

03:51.915 --> 04:00.787
Then the Lord said to Moses, write this as a memorial in a book and recite it in the ears of Joshua, that I will utterly blot out the memory of Amalek from under heaven.

04:02.048 --> 04:09.458
And Moses built an altar and called the name of it, the Lord is my banner, saying, a hand upon the throne of the Lord,

04:09.666 --> 04:13.330
The Lord will have war with Amalek from generation to generation.

04:14.911 --> 04:16.372
Now here's some questions, okay?

04:16.633 --> 04:21.698
About this idea that what this story is about is about prayer.

04:21.758 --> 04:29.865
As we've read that story, does it anywhere in the passage say that Moses was praying?

04:31.407 --> 04:31.807
It doesn't.

04:32.808 --> 04:35.611
It doesn't say that Aaron and her were praying either.

04:36.612 --> 04:38.834
So if it's not about prayer, what is it about?

04:39.362 --> 04:40.824
Well, first the setting.

04:41.085 --> 04:44.049
The story in Exodus starts rather abruptly.

04:44.089 --> 04:44.870
It starts this way.

04:44.910 --> 04:52.642
It says then Amalek came and fought with Israel at Raphidim, which there's actually a bit more backstory to what's going on here.

04:53.283 --> 04:58.811
If you want to go back in history, the Amalekites were the descendants of a guy named Esau.

04:59.793 --> 05:04.780
Esau was the older and the more impulsive brother of a guy named Isaac.

05:04.841 --> 05:08.466
And of course, Isaac was the forefather of the nation of Israel.

05:08.866 --> 05:14.555
He was a, Isaac was the father, the younger brother of Esau was Jacob, okay?

05:14.575 --> 05:16.779
So Jacob and Esau, the two brothers.

05:17.701 --> 05:24.252
As the older brother, Esau and their culture was entitled to the birthright.

05:24.772 --> 05:31.564
That was a legal claim to the majority of the fathers of state as well as authority over the family.

05:31.624 --> 05:33.026
That was his by right.

05:34.328 --> 05:35.410
Now it turns out,

05:35.586 --> 05:41.975
that Esau, as you read his story, you realize this was a guy who didn't spend too much time thinking about his 401k.

05:43.196 --> 05:45.539
He wasn't a real future planner if you get my meaning.

05:46.321 --> 05:48.864
And appears to have been a guy that really lived for the moment.

05:50.026 --> 05:53.851
The younger brother, Jacob, definitely was thinking about the future.

05:54.432 --> 05:57.516
He was a little smarter strategically than his older brother.

05:57.556 --> 06:02.162
And he knew how to answer the door when opportunity knocked.

06:02.754 --> 06:13.249
And so one afternoon, as the story goes, Jacob was cooking up this nice stew when Esau, who's been out hunting, working hard, shows up, and he's famished.

06:13.269 --> 06:19.258
And after this long day of hunting, Esau said that man, he would give anything for some of that stew.

06:20.300 --> 06:22.343
And Jacob heard opportunity knocking.

06:23.364 --> 06:27.811
And he said, well, how about if we swap stew for birthright?

06:29.093 --> 06:32.658
And foolishly, Esau agrees.

06:32.994 --> 06:35.558
It's kind of like, sure, the birthright, that's just a word.

06:35.578 --> 06:36.219
What does that mean?

06:36.299 --> 06:36.820
I'm starving.

06:36.860 --> 06:37.762
You can have the birthright.

06:37.822 --> 06:38.443
I don't care.

06:38.483 --> 06:45.254
Now, as you read the story, these two brothers, you'll find out that there were some other shenanigans that followed after that.

06:45.434 --> 06:51.885
Jacob kept getting the better of Esau, and that did not create much in the way of familial harmony.

06:52.967 --> 06:57.394
So some grudges were formed, and grudges like that get passed along.

06:57.538 --> 07:00.481
Jacob's descendants, as I said, were the children of Israel.

07:00.962 --> 07:04.165
Esau's descendants included the Amalekites.

07:04.886 --> 07:08.950
So the Amalekites didn't mind Israel living as slaves in Egypt.

07:08.990 --> 07:10.031
They were fine with that.

07:10.752 --> 07:14.856
They didn't much care for them, though, being tourists coming through their land.

07:15.397 --> 07:17.118
And so that sets up the conflict.

07:18.119 --> 07:20.342
There may have been some water rights involved as well.

07:20.542 --> 07:24.466
You remember that Exodus records this fight happened at Refidim?

07:24.802 --> 07:29.610
And you may recall that refedim is where God performed that miracle of water coming from the rock.

07:30.391 --> 07:35.079
And so whereas refedim had normally been a watering source, it appears that it had gone dry.

07:35.099 --> 07:38.564
And when you live in a desert region, water is a precious commodity.

07:38.604 --> 07:45.095
So suddenly, here's all these people coming through needing water, needing resources that may have played into this conflict.

07:46.598 --> 07:50.284
Finally, it appears that the amylakites were opportunists.

07:50.364 --> 07:51.826
They were desert marauders.

07:52.258 --> 07:56.022
We get more details about this fight when we get to the book of Deuteronomy.

07:56.963 --> 08:07.676
And in fact, as we've been going through this story of Israel and the Exodus, maybe you've noticed we've jumped at times from Exodus to Deuteronomy and you're thinking, what's the deal here?

08:07.936 --> 08:09.658
They seem like they're parallel accounts.

08:10.379 --> 08:15.825
And what happens is Exodus records the history of Israel exiting Egypt, right?

08:15.865 --> 08:16.786
The Exodus.

08:16.866 --> 08:18.488
making their way toward the Promised Land.

08:18.509 --> 08:23.216
Deuteronomy is kind of Moses' swan song.

08:23.897 --> 08:34.353
When Moses learned that he was not going to be allowed to go into the Promised Land, Deuteronomy becomes his final message to the people that he's led for 40 years.

08:34.433 --> 08:37.418
And as part of that message, he recounts their history.

08:38.199 --> 08:41.264
And along with that, he gives them warnings, he gives them wisdom.

08:41.324 --> 08:44.128
And so that's why you oftentimes find these parallel accounts.

08:44.168 --> 08:45.490
Exodus records it.

08:45.826 --> 08:51.295
Moses recites it again as part of his last message to the people of Israel.

08:51.836 --> 08:57.606
So here's what we find in Deuteronomy 25 that goes back to this issue with the Amalekites at Refidim.

08:59.369 --> 09:11.890
Remember what Amalek did to you on the way as you came out of Egypt, how he attacked you on the way when you were faint and weary and cut off your tail, those who were lagging behind you and he did not fear God.

09:12.546 --> 09:17.274
So what you find out from this is that this did not start as a fair fight.

09:17.354 --> 09:20.339
This was not like two armies that arrayed themselves for battle.

09:20.739 --> 09:24.706
He says, no, Amulet came out, and they were taking out the stragglers.

09:25.427 --> 09:28.592
They were coming up from behind, and so who would be behind?

09:28.672 --> 09:37.266
Well, it would be probably women, children, the aged, the ones that couldn't keep up, because understand, this is a lot of people that are moving.

09:37.538 --> 09:44.247
And so this column probably stretched out over a span of possibly miles from the head of the column to the tail.

09:44.807 --> 09:47.471
And he says, these amylakites, they saw opportunity.

09:47.491 --> 09:51.156
They're coming up and they're marauding from the back, taking out the weak.

09:51.696 --> 09:59.807
And so you can imagine the time it took for the message to get from the back of the line up to the head of the column to say, Moses, we've got problems back here.

09:59.827 --> 10:02.550
There are marauders back here attacking the weak.

10:03.351 --> 10:05.394
And so that is what sets us up.

10:05.698 --> 10:06.960
for this battle.

10:07.020 --> 10:12.267
It also gives some better perspective as to why the judgment against Amalek was so harsh.

10:13.249 --> 10:17.895
They had been these people that were marauding and assaulting the weak among Israel.

10:19.277 --> 10:24.124
So as soon as Moses learns about what's going on at the rear of the caravan, he calls for his fighters.

10:24.285 --> 10:28.050
And the man that he turns to first is this guy named Joshua.

10:28.482 --> 10:30.524
Of course, you probably are from the Joshua.

10:30.564 --> 10:33.848
Joshua, ultimately, will be the leader that replaces Moses.

10:34.248 --> 10:35.630
But that is years down the road.

10:35.650 --> 10:36.431
That's going to happen.

10:36.831 --> 10:44.139
This is actually the first time that we hear Joshua's name is showing up in this battle with Amalek.

10:44.399 --> 10:49.685
And his appearance here tells us that Joshua was already a known and trusted leader.

10:50.066 --> 10:52.428
We'll talk more about Joshua in a few weeks.

10:53.169 --> 10:57.714
But he was recognized by Moses right away as the right man

10:57.794 --> 10:58.655
to lead the fight.

10:59.996 --> 11:03.841
We're told that Joshua is told to go out and to draft an army.

11:04.622 --> 11:06.444
Moses says, go out and choose men for us.

11:07.625 --> 11:15.273
At this point, we talked about this few weeks ago, God had intentionally led Israel around points of conflict.

11:15.834 --> 11:23.242
They could have found themselves in battle sooner with other people, and God intentionally led them around it because they weren't ready to fight.

11:24.063 --> 11:26.706
But this time, there's no getting around the fight.

11:27.042 --> 11:28.764
The fight has come to them.

11:28.824 --> 11:30.566
Amalek has come after them.

11:30.627 --> 11:36.254
And it would appear that there wasn't yet any kind of a formal militia established, right?

11:36.274 --> 11:38.456
That has not been on the to-do list so far.

11:39.017 --> 11:43.843
Moses says to Joshua, we've got to pull some men together so that we can defend ourselves.

11:44.344 --> 11:49.470
And so that's Joshua's job, to find that fighting force and then go fight the Amalekites.

11:50.592 --> 11:55.538
As for Moses, he lets Joshua know that what he's going to do

11:55.650 --> 12:03.903
He's going to place himself in this prominent position up at the top of a hill, and he's going to be holding up, he says, the staff of God.

12:05.165 --> 12:08.690
When we started this study, we began with the story of Passover.

12:09.011 --> 12:13.638
That was the point which officially launched the Exodus from Egypt.

12:14.680 --> 12:18.906
But the things Moses had done prior to that were an important prequel.

12:19.968 --> 12:23.954
Moses' staff was central to those events.

12:24.322 --> 12:28.891
The first time that we encounter the staff goes all the way back to that burning bush.

12:29.693 --> 12:30.895
Remember the story of the burning bush?

12:30.975 --> 12:38.130
Moses is out there being a shepherd just minding his own business and suddenly he's confronted by this bush that's in flames but the bush isn't burning.

12:38.891 --> 12:42.258
And he approaches it and it is God's presence.

12:42.530 --> 12:44.012
And God speaks to him.

12:44.032 --> 12:46.576
He says, take off your sandals, you're standing on holy ground.

12:46.937 --> 12:54.889
And that's when God tells him that he's going to be sent back to his people to deliver them from Egypt, which sounds like a pretty tall task.

12:55.630 --> 13:02.380
And Moses didn't think that anybody was going to believe that this really was the mission God had sent him on.

13:02.420 --> 13:06.607
It's like, why are they going to believe if I show up and say, God sent me to deliver you, you know?

13:07.408 --> 13:07.508
Hi.

13:08.229 --> 13:11.314
And so here's what God says, or what Moses says first.

13:11.714 --> 13:15.379
Moses answered, behold, they will not believe me or listen to my voice.

13:15.419 --> 13:17.382
They'll say, the Lord did not appear to you.

13:18.063 --> 13:20.427
The Lord said to him, what is that in your hand?

13:21.208 --> 13:22.650
And he said, a staff?

13:23.271 --> 13:24.412
And he said, throw it on the ground.

13:24.452 --> 13:26.395
So he threw it on the ground and became a serpent.

13:26.996 --> 13:28.138
And Moses ran from it.

13:28.618 --> 13:31.643
And here we learned that Moses was afraid of snakes, OK?

13:33.666 --> 13:36.550
But the Lord said to Moses, put out your hand and catch it by the tail.

13:36.670 --> 13:39.474
So he put out his hand, caught it, and became a staff in his hand.

13:40.130 --> 13:47.519
that they may believe that the Lord, the God of their fathers, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac and the God of Jacob has appeared to you.

13:47.979 --> 13:56.088
So right away God says this staff is going to play an important role in validating that in fact I am the one who has sent you to deliver the people.

13:56.809 --> 14:07.922
Well then as Moses goes back as he begins to confront Pharaoh with this message to let the people go and Pharaoh keeps saying I'm not going to let the people go, we have that series of plagues.

14:08.066 --> 14:12.732
And in several of these plagues, again, we find that the staff plays an important role.

14:13.213 --> 14:18.761
For instance, when the Nile is turned to blood, Moses is holding the staff in his hand.

14:19.441 --> 14:24.889
Or when we have the story of the plague of hail, Moses stretched out his staff toward heaven.

14:24.929 --> 14:27.032
The Lord sent thunder and hail.

14:27.733 --> 14:30.376
Or the plague of the locus, once again.

14:31.137 --> 14:34.001
Moses stretched out his staff over the land of Egypt.

14:34.121 --> 14:37.586
The Lord brought an east wind on the land, all that day, all that night.

14:37.666 --> 14:39.349
The East wind brought the locus.

14:40.070 --> 14:45.219
Or when you get, they finally get released from Egypt and we come to them at the Red Sea.

14:45.259 --> 14:47.783
They're trapped between Pharaoh's army and the Red Sea.

14:47.823 --> 14:49.145
They see no way of escape.

14:49.766 --> 14:53.292
And once again, we're told that the Lord is going to deliver them.

14:53.793 --> 15:03.730
He says, tell the people of Israel, go forward, lift up your staff, stretch out your hand over the sea and divide it that the people of Israel may go through the sea on dry ground.

15:04.418 --> 15:13.527
And of course, last week, we looked at the story of water from a rock and how the Lord said to Moses, I want you to take your staff and to strike the rock.

15:13.547 --> 15:17.310
And we talked in detail about what that story was all about.

15:17.971 --> 15:21.354
Well, now, once again, we have this battle with Amalek.

15:21.875 --> 15:23.857
And Moses says, I'm going to go up on the hilltop.

15:24.157 --> 15:26.519
I'm going to have the staff of God in my hand.

15:26.559 --> 15:27.840
I'm going to hold that aloft.

15:29.142 --> 15:32.084
So the question is, what was the staff of God?

15:32.205 --> 15:33.746
Why is that so important?

15:34.850 --> 15:42.840
Well, I'd say first it was the symbolic representation of God's power to judge and protect his people.

15:43.861 --> 15:47.766
Now, when God first came to Moses, Moses out there being a shepherd to sheep.

15:48.426 --> 15:50.008
A staff was the shepherd's tool.

15:50.869 --> 15:52.852
It was how he guided his sheep.

15:52.872 --> 15:54.634
It was how he protected his sheep.

15:54.714 --> 16:01.362
And so it's that tool that God says, this becomes a symbol of my power and my presence with you.

16:01.922 --> 16:05.327
It also validated Moses as God's chosen instrument.

16:05.567 --> 16:07.610
He says, if they say, did God really send you?

16:07.650 --> 16:13.739
He says, this becomes the evidence that God has sent me to bring deliverance.

16:15.482 --> 16:24.935
I think that making it something separate from Moses himself, though made it clear that the power Moses was wielding was not his own.

16:26.017 --> 16:29.522
I mean, God could have given Moses magic fingers, right?

16:30.402 --> 16:31.423
But he doesn't do that.

16:31.483 --> 16:34.907
It's like this is not just about Moses having power.

16:35.988 --> 16:40.073
This is about Moses being chosen to wield God's power.

16:40.113 --> 16:44.158
And so the symbol of God's power becomes something separate from Moses himself.

16:45.619 --> 16:51.186
So was Moses holding the staff and act of prayer?

16:52.427 --> 16:53.268
Well, I don't think so.

16:53.328 --> 16:58.354
This staff had been this sign of assurance to Moses that God was with him.

16:58.978 --> 17:04.525
It was a sign of God's presence and his power, both to Pharaoh and to Israel.

17:05.906 --> 17:11.212
Moses never bowed to the staff, like he might have bowed before an altar.

17:11.733 --> 17:13.615
He didn't pray to the staff.

17:14.696 --> 17:19.522
The times that he went to meet with God, he either went into the 10th meeting or went up on Mount Sinai.

17:19.542 --> 17:21.364
He didn't go to meet with the staff.

17:22.586 --> 17:26.290
The staff always served as a symbol of God's power,

17:26.370 --> 17:34.602
being present with and providing for his people with Moses being his chosen agent through whom that power was being mediated.

17:36.265 --> 17:43.917
Now in terms of the battle itself, there's not much detail given other than it went well and it went badly by spells.

17:44.938 --> 17:50.867
The whole focus of the drama is placed on Moses holding the staff aloft.

17:50.887 --> 17:55.474
When the staff is held high, we're told that Joshua and his fighters get the upper hand.

17:55.714 --> 18:01.020
When the staff drops down, Joshua's troops find themselves on the defensive.

18:01.200 --> 18:03.202
That is really the crux of the story.

18:04.464 --> 18:06.646
The battle was not a short one.

18:07.727 --> 18:10.830
We find that Moses gets tired in the course of what he's doing.

18:10.871 --> 18:13.133
Now, Moses had been a shepherd for 40 years.

18:13.794 --> 18:16.637
He'd been leading the people on this long trek in the wilderness.

18:17.318 --> 18:20.041
So I'm guessing this guy had pretty good standing power.

18:21.022 --> 18:25.106
And yet, things drug onto the point that Moses needed to sit down.

18:25.346 --> 18:27.129
So we have this account of Erin and her.

18:27.189 --> 18:29.252
They get him a nice, comfortable rock.

18:30.194 --> 18:34.360
They brought the rock to him so he could stay in that highly visible position.

18:35.281 --> 18:39.448
And we're told that not only his legs got tired, but his arms started giving out as well.

18:40.570 --> 18:44.556
Judging from the text appears, he might have tried both hands, right?

18:44.676 --> 18:47.921
First it says he held up his hand whenever he lowered his hand.

18:48.362 --> 18:51.186
And then we find his hands, plural, grew weary.

18:51.618 --> 18:55.442
So it's almost like, man, he did this arm for a while and he did this arm for a while and tried both arms for a while.

18:55.502 --> 18:57.605
And finally, he's just out of energy.

18:57.645 --> 19:05.173
And so you find Aaron and her helping him out, which Aaron and her positioned themselves to support him.

19:06.254 --> 19:10.539
And it wasn't just the staff that mattered in this equation.

19:11.720 --> 19:15.605
If it was, Moses could just handed it off to one of those two guys.

19:15.665 --> 19:16.626
He'd say, here, hang on to this.

19:16.686 --> 19:17.367
Just keep it high.

19:17.387 --> 19:18.188
That's all that matters.

19:18.968 --> 19:20.370
And yet Moses

19:20.450 --> 19:22.853
was the one through whom God was leading the people.

19:22.934 --> 19:28.962
It again, established Moses as the leader, even though he wasn't personally down there in the fight.

19:30.224 --> 19:32.407
And so they had to stay there until night fell.

19:33.229 --> 19:35.151
And so it's a long battle last all day.

19:35.211 --> 19:37.715
And finally, Joshua gains the upper hand.

19:38.396 --> 19:43.964
And maybe due to cover of darkness, the Amalekites were finally able to break contact and sneak away.

19:44.024 --> 19:48.050
In the aftermath, two things happened.

19:48.578 --> 20:04.276
The first is that the Lord told Moses to write a memorial and recited in the ears of Joshua, which is interesting because you would think that Joshua, who had been in the battle, wouldn't need anyone to remind him about what had happened.

20:04.316 --> 20:05.277
He had lived it.

20:06.339 --> 20:10.183
And yet what God wanted Joshua to know was that he wasn't done with Amalek yet.

20:11.064 --> 20:12.786
Amalek was still lurking out there.

20:13.218 --> 20:20.449
And the day would come when Joshua and the leaders who came after him would have to deal with Amalek once and for all.

20:21.871 --> 20:25.036
The message is, Joshua, you're not to make peace with Amalek.

20:25.056 --> 20:29.483
We're not gonna follow that history out, but if you were to follow the history, you'd find in fact that was true.

20:30.084 --> 20:33.149
Amalek comes back in Israel's history and has to be dealt with again.

20:33.209 --> 20:38.858
The second thing we find is that Moses built an altar to the Lord.

20:39.859 --> 20:41.682
And he gave the altar an interesting name.

20:42.178 --> 20:45.082
He named the altar, the Lord is my banner.

20:45.883 --> 20:49.327
And then he said, this battle with Amalek would stretch across generations.

20:50.288 --> 20:58.098
And so Moses is saying that the battle would always be the Lord's as long as God's people stayed true to God as their leader.

21:00.000 --> 21:08.211
Now I started with that thesis that the story of Moses holding the staff aloft is not primarily a call to prayer.

21:09.052 --> 21:10.994
Even though I've often heard it treated as such.

21:11.650 --> 21:15.335
And don't get me wrong, I'm all for prayer, okay?

21:15.355 --> 21:21.544
So if you go home and say, wow, Pastor Tim said we shouldn't pray, you didn't hear the sermon, okay?

21:21.584 --> 21:25.590
In fact, we're gonna, because I believe there is an element of prayer in this, all right?

21:25.650 --> 21:27.473
I just don't think that's the central message.

21:28.554 --> 21:32.981
A couple things I don't like about just turning this into a metaphor for prayer.

21:33.962 --> 21:36.345
First is, like I said, I don't think that Moses was praying.

21:37.227 --> 21:39.570
I mean, I do think he was praying,

21:39.778 --> 21:43.063
but holding the staff aloft itself was not an act of prayer.

21:43.183 --> 21:44.405
It was a declaration.

21:45.066 --> 21:50.155
It was a declaration of God's power and presence and authority with his people.

21:51.437 --> 22:01.493
The second thing I don't like about turning it just into a metaphor for prayer is I think it can distort our understanding of the practice of prayer.

22:02.655 --> 22:07.282
We can begin to think that God's answers to prayer are contingent on

22:07.714 --> 22:10.977
our intensity or even our physical sacrifice.

22:12.078 --> 22:23.489
If the reason that Israel prevailed was because of Moses' intensity, because of Moses' hard work, because Moses held the staff aloft, and we say, well, that's what prayer is like.

22:24.049 --> 22:31.116
Unless we stay intense enough, unless we sacrifice enough, God won't be able to act.

22:32.417 --> 22:37.682
You can go to some really unhealthy places in your understanding about prayer in that sense.

22:38.690 --> 22:44.116
suddenly the ritual of how we pray can begin to seem as important as the prayer itself.

22:45.938 --> 22:51.224
I don't think that Moses went up on the hill and raised the staff so that God could see him better.

22:52.806 --> 22:55.209
He wasn't trying to get God's attention, right?

22:55.229 --> 22:56.110
That would be prayer.

22:56.170 --> 22:59.494
He was trying to get the attention of his warriors in the battle.

23:00.715 --> 23:06.482
Every time they glanced up from the battle, there was Moses holding the staff aloft at the top of the hill.

23:07.586 --> 23:20.148
The staff that had brought down plagues on Egypt, the staff that had secured their release, the staff that had split the Red Sea and allowed them to escape, the staff that had just struck the rock and brought forth life-saving water.

23:20.909 --> 23:29.263
The staff that declared that God was their shepherd, he was their defender, or as Moses named the altar, the Lord was their banner.

23:30.305 --> 23:33.170
He was the one who was under his authority that they were fighting.

23:34.306 --> 23:42.156
In all of those prior instances, all the other times they had seen the staff raised, they really had been just passive observers, right?

23:42.837 --> 23:45.520
They simply had watched Moses wield the staff.

23:45.941 --> 23:50.687
They hadn't done anything to do except take advantage of the opportunities.

23:51.207 --> 23:52.809
They walked to freedom.

23:52.849 --> 23:54.271
They got a drink of water.

23:55.212 --> 23:56.233
But this time is different.

23:57.455 --> 23:59.858
This time, they're in a fight.

24:00.610 --> 24:02.633
They don't just get to stand back and watch.

24:02.673 --> 24:04.135
They actually have to enter in.

24:05.376 --> 24:10.163
And the temptation could have been in that fight to think that the winning was all up to them.

24:11.625 --> 24:20.116
Every time they looked up at the hill, they saw Moses holding the staff aloft, declaring that we are God's people.

24:21.278 --> 24:27.666
And when the staff came down, when they began to think that the battle is just about us, they begin losing ground.

24:29.026 --> 24:32.129
So the message was you need to fight, but you don't fight alone.

24:32.209 --> 24:34.531
This success still demands on God's power.

24:35.993 --> 24:41.678
And in case they weren't sure how much they needed God's power, every time the staff dropped, they started losing ground.

24:43.340 --> 24:46.943
Which also told them there was more to the fight than just swords and spears.

24:48.224 --> 24:49.886
There was something else going on.

24:50.747 --> 24:53.669
Something they couldn't just quantify in the physical realm.

24:54.330 --> 24:58.514
It's like, why are we being less effective now than we were then?

24:59.266 --> 25:00.768
Well, it's because there's more going on.

25:01.690 --> 25:08.480
God is with you behind the scenes, sovereign over the situation, so that you can win this fight.

25:10.923 --> 25:12.586
So what can we take away from this passage?

25:13.267 --> 25:17.413
And I, quite honestly, I've wrestled a lot with this passage.

25:17.433 --> 25:19.456
And I'm not sure I've brought it to the ground yet.

25:19.656 --> 25:21.318
Some of you may have greater insight than me.

25:21.358 --> 25:23.762
That's just fine.

25:25.762 --> 25:28.386
Again, I'm not saying this that we don't need to pray.

25:28.426 --> 25:33.753
In fact, I'm gonna talk about an aspect of prayer that I think is really important that plays into this.

25:35.095 --> 25:40.183
But I think this story has a lot to remind us of how we face conflict.

25:41.424 --> 25:45.971
There are times when God in his kindness saves us from the fight.

25:47.393 --> 25:51.899
I think sometimes we don't even know we've been saved from the fight, but God has saved us from the fight.

25:51.960 --> 25:53.682
Situations we thought

25:53.890 --> 25:57.274
We're gonna bring conflicts, suddenly resolve themselves peaceably.

25:58.235 --> 26:03.501
Things that we have worried about and kept awake at night with nervous anticipation.

26:03.521 --> 26:04.562
I don't know if you've ever done that.

26:04.702 --> 26:05.863
I've done it once or twice.

26:05.923 --> 26:08.846
They end up being nothing.

26:09.747 --> 26:11.770
It's like the fight doesn't happen.

26:12.651 --> 26:15.454
And we say, God, thank you for saving me from the fight.

26:15.534 --> 26:18.717
But there are also times when the Amalekite show up.

26:20.159 --> 26:22.962
People or situations that cannot be avoided

26:23.266 --> 26:27.810
and that seem intent to do us harm, and we can't avoid the fight.

26:27.850 --> 26:28.931
It comes to us.

26:30.373 --> 26:34.176
There appear to be these times that God wants us to face the conflict.

26:35.257 --> 26:42.444
I mean, why couldn't God have simply done a miracle to defeat the Amalekites without Joshua ever stepping into the battle?

26:44.126 --> 26:46.528
He could have, but he didn't.

26:47.749 --> 26:52.093
In this situation, Israel was expected to step into the fight.

26:52.113 --> 26:53.074
They had to face

26:53.250 --> 27:01.185
conflict and there are times in all of our lives that like it or not we have conflict that we have to face.

27:02.247 --> 27:04.211
The question is how do we face it?

27:04.511 --> 27:08.038
What does it look like to face conflict as God's people?

27:11.204 --> 27:16.434
One of the things I pick up from this story is that when conflict comes

27:17.314 --> 27:18.857
You should marshal your best defenses.

27:19.117 --> 27:21.802
Moses didn't just send people out willy-nilly.

27:21.862 --> 27:25.889
He didn't send the women and the children and the infirm and the elderly out to fight.

27:25.989 --> 27:27.572
He picked a strong leader.

27:27.952 --> 27:30.797
He got Joshua and he said, go find strong warriors.

27:31.719 --> 27:35.385
So you want to use some intelligence about how you come at the conflict.

27:36.507 --> 27:38.130
You look for wise counselors.

27:38.434 --> 27:43.000
people who can help you to prepare well and support you in the conflict.

27:43.060 --> 27:51.753
I think as a follower of Jesus, that means we look for counsel and support from counselors who themselves are experienced followers of Jesus.

27:52.934 --> 27:55.678
The world has a lot of suggestions about how to face a fight.

27:57.120 --> 27:58.702
They're not all true wisdom.

27:59.944 --> 28:07.154
Find people who really are committed to Jesus to help you decide what is a Jesus kind of strategy to deal with conflict.

28:08.546 --> 28:13.153
Second thing I would say is we need to hold the staff high and keep it in our sights.

28:13.173 --> 28:14.355
And here's what I mean by that.

28:15.297 --> 28:21.306
The staff was this visible reminder to Joshua that they were not alone in the battle.

28:22.488 --> 28:28.217
It was a reminder that they were part of a tribe that was loved and chosen and protected by the Lord.

28:28.277 --> 28:30.901
The Lord was their shepherd.

28:32.243 --> 28:34.226
And he's ours as well, right?

28:34.306 --> 28:38.511
Jesus uses that image to talk about us as His flock and He is our shepherd.

28:39.672 --> 28:41.354
And this is where I think prayer does come in.

28:42.295 --> 28:47.822
Not so much that we have to work hard enough, do enough to get God to listen to us.

28:47.902 --> 28:48.863
God is listening.

28:49.644 --> 28:51.126
We should pray He wants to hear.

28:52.047 --> 29:01.298
But the thing that I think helps us to keep our gaze from becoming trapped in the immediacy of the conflict is praise.

29:02.178 --> 29:05.662
I love the selection of songs that Vernon and the team have this morning.

29:06.122 --> 29:11.128
Songs of praise that keep reminding us that we are not in the fight alone.

29:12.289 --> 29:13.230
God is with us.

29:13.410 --> 29:14.631
God is our shepherd.

29:15.612 --> 29:26.925
And so that part of prayer, I say amen, that that for sure is a way that we lift our eyes like the soldiers fighting with the Amalekites kept looking up to the hill and going, yep, we are God's people.

29:26.985 --> 29:28.306
God is with us.

29:28.418 --> 29:34.467
praise is one of the ways that we refocus our hearts, remind ourselves that we are not in this alone.

29:34.507 --> 29:40.576
The problem is when we get into conflict that drags on and on, it's the long conflicts.

29:40.596 --> 29:44.221
I'm pretty good at looking at handling it great with short conflicts.

29:45.143 --> 29:49.469
Give me a test for a day and man, I can pray my way through that and praise the Lord and move on.

29:50.010 --> 29:55.378
But let it drag on for a couple weeks or a couple months or a couple years.

29:55.778 --> 30:01.987
And it's real easy to let my gay shift from here down to here and get that sort of tunnel vision.

30:02.748 --> 30:08.337
And when I get that way, I start using the wrong strategies.

30:09.919 --> 30:11.662
I start trying to win the wrong way.

30:13.244 --> 30:25.362
If you move side of who you are and under whose banner you live, I think your strategies become those of a panicked person, which means it's no holds barred, whatever it takes to win.

30:26.178 --> 30:29.421
Bitterness can replace wisdom.

30:31.083 --> 30:33.025
Bitterness takes the place of forgiveness.

30:35.447 --> 30:40.572
It's imperative when we're in conflict to remember under whose banner we fight.

30:41.813 --> 30:45.837
We fight under the banner of the Lamb who died and rose again.

30:45.877 --> 30:50.421
My wife has found a little phrase that she's been quoting the last few weeks.

30:50.802 --> 30:52.743
Says, trust the man who died for you.

30:52.783 --> 30:55.506
It's under his banner that we fight.

30:56.674 --> 31:09.669
And that means that our strategies always have to conform to his, which means that winning in the conflict may look very different at times from how the world views winning.

31:11.291 --> 31:24.466
Jesus talked about those who followed him to his win, being people who would take up a cross, people who would be willing to sacrifice, and also means that winning in the way of the world

31:25.058 --> 31:28.322
may actually be losing in the battle that matters most.

31:29.524 --> 31:31.426
The Apostle Paul, of course, made that point.

31:31.626 --> 31:33.689
You probably know the verse, Ephesians 6.

31:34.250 --> 31:39.697
He says, we do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly places.

31:40.257 --> 31:42.120
In other words, Paul said there's more going on here.

31:43.061 --> 31:50.130
Just like Joshua facing the Amalekites, it's like there's more going on here than just soldier to soldier having a conflict.

31:50.754 --> 31:55.463
Because when your eyes understand on whose banner you fight, the battle goes well.

31:55.564 --> 31:58.089
You take your eyes off of that, the battle does not go well.

31:58.990 --> 32:04.902
And Paul says, don't forget, the conflicts you're in are not just about that person.

32:06.045 --> 32:08.269
There is a spiritual reality here as well.

32:09.972 --> 32:12.818
Our thought of second Corinthians, I don't have it on the screen.

32:13.506 --> 32:22.499
It says our present troubles are small and won't last very long, and yet they produce for us a glory that vastly outweighs them and will last forever.

32:23.059 --> 32:26.584
So we don't look at the troubles we can see now.

32:27.365 --> 32:30.490
Rather, we fix our gaze on things that cannot be seen.

32:31.271 --> 32:36.959
For the things we see now will soon be gone, but the things we cannot see will last forever.

32:38.261 --> 32:39.903
Again, it's this focus.

32:40.083 --> 32:42.066
Where do my eyes turn?

32:42.338 --> 32:44.521
in the midst of conflict, in the midst of struggle.

32:46.563 --> 32:48.505
I don't know what the conflicts are you're facing right now.

32:49.907 --> 32:56.414
There's probably no one in this room that isn't facing some kind of conflict, some kind of battle.

32:57.375 --> 33:00.098
Maybe it is a battle within your own family.

33:01.640 --> 33:10.130
As a pastor over the years, I have seen lots of people get entangled in some pretty ugly and protracted family disputes.

33:11.362 --> 33:18.110
Many of you have gone through the pain of divorce and you understand the conflict and the pain that comes with that.

33:19.272 --> 33:23.417
Or maybe it's been a conflict over aging parents or the settling of an estate.

33:24.538 --> 33:33.490
Or maybe it's been a family members addiction or some dysfunction that has thrown relationships into chaos and caused all kinds of conflict.

33:34.851 --> 33:40.338
And again, when those things drag on for a week after week and month after month and year after year,

33:40.930 --> 33:45.176
It's easy to forget under whose banner we are to face conflict.

33:46.779 --> 33:56.093
And sometimes we need Jesus' loving friends who can come alongside us and help us to once again lift the cross high above the battle.

33:57.075 --> 34:02.202
To help lift our focus up again and say, under whose banner do we fight?

34:04.245 --> 34:06.329
Maybe it's a literal physical battle.

34:07.210 --> 34:09.874
Maybe you're dealing with chronic illness, some kind of

34:10.018 --> 34:12.341
pain and for me to just won't stop.

34:13.463 --> 34:19.492
I saw a quip recently, it said that middle aged that time of life when you still believe it'll be better in the morning.

34:23.037 --> 34:39.442
You know, I'd have to say that some of the most humble, kind, faithful people that I've known over the years have been people who have lived with long-term illness, and yet they've kept their gaze on Jesus.

34:40.610 --> 34:43.134
A lot of us know the story of Johnny Eric's and Tata.

34:43.774 --> 35:01.820
To me, she's a class example of someone who has faced great physical challenges, a quadriplegic since she was a young woman, lived her life out with all of the complications that presents, and yet to know Johnny's story is to see someone who is filled with joy.

35:03.202 --> 35:09.170
Not because life isn't difficult, not because the pain hasn't gone on for years and years and years,

35:09.346 --> 35:14.073
but because she's someone who has a heart who has kept her eyes on the banner.

35:15.815 --> 35:21.784
She still lifts her voice in praise, and she's had an incredible impact on so many because of that.

35:23.166 --> 35:31.638
But I've also known people who turned inward and became despondent and bitter and full of self-pity in the midst of those battles.

35:33.601 --> 35:37.106
Psalm 23, again, I don't have this on the screen,

35:37.410 --> 35:43.037
Part of what it says is, though I walk through the valley of the shadow of death, I will fear no evil.

35:43.658 --> 35:46.261
Your rod and your staff, they come from me.

35:46.321 --> 35:47.483
There comes the staff again.

35:47.503 --> 35:53.029
I've made the point in another context that in that Psalm, he says, though I walk through the valley.

35:54.071 --> 35:56.354
In other words, there are some valleys you have to go through.

35:56.374 --> 36:03.062
I'd rather go around the valley of the shadow of death or fly over it or just not even go there.

36:03.863 --> 36:06.386
But he says, no, there are times you have to go through the valley

36:07.010 --> 36:09.113
And you walk.

36:09.133 --> 36:12.397
I wouldn't mind running, skipping, jumping something, but no, you walk.

36:12.597 --> 36:17.142
There is a slow process sometimes of going through that dark valley.

36:17.683 --> 36:21.528
And yet the promise in it is the shepherd is still there.

36:23.310 --> 36:24.611
His staff is still with you.

36:25.753 --> 36:26.774
And so don't lose heart.

36:28.656 --> 36:30.478
Maybe it's a conflict in your workplace.

36:32.040 --> 36:34.503
Boy, that can consume an awful lot of emotional energy, can it?

36:35.264 --> 36:36.786
And break into open warfare?

36:37.442 --> 36:45.471
I've told the story before about a friend of mine years ago in California had a boss that these two just, oh my goodness, it got ugly.

36:46.031 --> 36:48.014
And this guy would come and talk to you about it.

36:48.274 --> 36:50.576
And we had talked about forgiveness.

36:51.177 --> 36:56.923
And he just could not see any way that he could forgive this jerk for the way he treated him.

36:56.943 --> 36:58.024
And it got so bad.

36:58.064 --> 37:03.330
He got so angry as a boss, he finally came and confessed to me that he was having dreams about murdering his boss.

37:04.892 --> 37:06.834
And I'm like, you know, you really got to handle that, you know?

37:07.010 --> 37:15.322
So we talked about forgiveness, and he finally, he wrestled through, he prayed through, and he said, yeah, this is the banner that I face conflict on her.

37:15.603 --> 37:16.945
My banner is the Lord.

37:18.367 --> 37:20.410
And so the time came, he sat down with his boss.

37:21.371 --> 37:22.613
They talked about the conflict.

37:23.595 --> 37:30.085
And my friend with fear and trembling said, I just want you to know that I, I've forgiven you for that stuff.

37:31.547 --> 37:32.949
Now, this had been a hard boss.

37:34.471 --> 37:36.434
He says this, not knowing what's gonna happen,

37:37.154 --> 37:45.643
The boss gets up from his chair, tears running down his face, comes around and gives this guy a hug, which he didn't know what to do.

37:45.683 --> 37:47.485
This was not the response he was looking for.

37:48.345 --> 37:57.615
But again, sometimes the change it makes when we decide to fight the way the Lord wants us to fight, not the way we want to fight in ourselves.

37:59.477 --> 38:04.562
Maybe the fight that's consuming you, consuming your emotions is this thing we call the culture wars.

38:04.802 --> 38:08.808
And for sure, there's lots of things in our culture that run counter to righteousness.

38:09.909 --> 38:11.251
But that's really nothing new.

38:12.272 --> 38:19.523
You can plunge your finger down in the history book on any page at any time and you will find all kinds of wickedness going on.

38:19.603 --> 38:21.365
It's a fallen world.

38:23.308 --> 38:33.362
But one of the things that has concerned me increasingly in our current time is how sometimes people who profess to march under the banner of Jesus wanting to fight for the right

38:34.338 --> 38:36.721
have chosen some of the strategy of the world to do it.

38:39.323 --> 38:45.270
For Christians, the sign of God's power and presence isn't the rod of Moses, it is the cross of Jesus.

38:46.571 --> 38:57.944
And so if you're being tempted to dip into anger or try to grab power or look for revenge or view your enemies with disdain, could I just say that's not how you fight under the banner of the cross?

39:00.847 --> 39:03.410
The Apostle Paul reminded Christians living in

39:04.034 --> 39:08.220
arguably even darker times that lowering their gains to a human level.

39:09.342 --> 39:14.149
Their political opponents, their religious detractors, he said, is to be consumed with the wrong battle.

39:15.510 --> 39:17.133
We don't wrestle against flesh and blood.

39:18.835 --> 39:21.639
The Amalekites the Christian fights are spiritual forces.

39:21.699 --> 39:24.804
The battle first and foremost is a spiritual battle.

39:25.565 --> 39:31.954
And it must be fought with the weapons of the cross to fight with anything else is ultimately to lose.

39:32.482 --> 39:36.566
to take our eyes off the man on the hill who died for us.

39:39.750 --> 39:45.816
For the follower of Jesus, our standard bearer is not an old man seated on a hill holding aloft his staff.

39:47.437 --> 39:59.570
It is a bleeding man high on a hill crucified on a cross, praying forgiveness over his enemies and radically sacrificing himself in love for the very people who put in there.

40:01.794 --> 40:11.426
So I just say if you are tiring in a battle, whatever that battle is, find someone who will help lift Jesus high before your eyes.

40:12.908 --> 40:15.972
Remind yourself under whose banner you fight.

40:17.935 --> 40:29.650
And if you have a friend who's in a battle, whatever that battle is, physical, emotional, spiritual, it's good to empathize, but don't forget

40:29.954 --> 40:31.757
to help them keep their eyes on the cross.

40:33.499 --> 40:37.285
Therein lies the victory that has always taken the world by surprise.

40:39.708 --> 40:45.056
May all of our battles be fought under his banner and using his strategy.

40:46.037 --> 40:46.318
Amen?

40:47.319 --> 40:47.700
Let's pray.

40:51.125 --> 40:57.554
Father, you know all of the battles that the people in this room represent.

40:59.618 --> 41:04.103
or things that we would rather avoid, and yet there it is.

41:04.443 --> 41:07.207
There are the Amalekites and we have to face it.

41:09.850 --> 41:15.296
I pray for my brothers and sisters this morning who are tired in whatever that conflict is.

41:17.659 --> 41:27.730
Lord, I pray that you would help their eyes to be lifted up to you, that you would in a fresh way remind them, that you have not forsaken them.

41:28.930 --> 41:33.395
You are the good shepherd who goes with us through the valley of the shadow of death.

41:35.096 --> 41:40.962
Your rod, your staff, your concern, your care is still with us, is still sovereign.

41:44.025 --> 41:53.115
Or if in getting our eyes turned off of you, we have allowed our hearts to become consumed in strategies that aren't your strategies.

41:54.596 --> 41:56.498
What I prayed you would free us from those things.

41:57.858 --> 42:08.211
Grannish your grace, may your spirit fill us and move us that we would face conflict in a way that honors Jesus.

42:09.793 --> 42:16.041
And if we didn't even know what that means, Lord, maybe we don't even know what it looks like in the fight we're facing, I pray you'd give us wisdom.

42:16.282 --> 42:17.583
I prayed you'd give us insight.

42:17.623 --> 42:21.589
You said that you would give us wisdom if we didn't know what to do.

42:21.669 --> 42:25.874
And so we would ask you for that wisdom, pray that you would give us

42:26.018 --> 42:35.295
Friends, counselors who are wise counselors who love you that would help us figure out what it looks like to meet our conflict in a way that honors you.

42:37.959 --> 42:44.271
Thank you, Lord, that we do not walk alone, that it is your banner that we live under.

42:46.315 --> 42:49.100
We pray this all in the name of Jesus who gave himself for us.

42:50.121 --> 42:50.482
Amen.

